en: The Life and Exploits of the ingenious gentleman Don Quixote de la Mancha
J. and R. Tonson and S. Draper, and R. Dodsley
Cervantes receives his arms to fight Chivalric Books

Allegorical frontispiece.Cervantes, as HerculesMusagetes(followed by the nine Muses), receives from a satyr the arms (Comedy mask) to fight the monsters (Chivalric books) that have invaded Mount Parnassus.Figures of great and classical beauty.Excellent drawing and engraving (Muses' faces, tunics, Hercules' musculature...).
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
1.1 DQ at his library reading chivalric novels

Don Quixote, dressed as a 18th century English gentleman, reads peacefully while he observes his family arms (on the wall); these, far from looking like "tomadas de orín y llenas de moho, luengos siglos había, que estaban puestas y olvidadas en un rincón" (1:1), appear new and neat.Drawing and engraving are good (don Quixote's figure, furniture, books, arms...); not so the room, too small, cold and without details.

1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after Vertue's plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738; in the original, there was a fireplace on the left too.
Don Quixote knighted by the innkeeper
3.4 DQ knighted at inn by innkeeper

In the center of the composition, don Quixote kneels before the innkeeper (holding a book and a sword).In the background, doña Molinera with don Quixote's spurs and doña Tolosa with his sword.In the foreground, a candle, held by a boy, creates interesting light and shadow effects (see innkeeper, don Quixote's armour...).Good drawing and engraving.

1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - The figure of the innkeeper has been attributed to William Hogarth.
Sancho asks don Quixote for the island he was promised to govern
10.1 SP asks DQ for his insula

After having defeated the Basque (fallen in the background with two Basque ladies), don Quixote is asked by Sancho for the government of his island; the knight tells Sancho that he must wait (see don Quixote's hand).Don Quixote and Sancho's figures are well-detailed drawn and engraved; their gestures and faces are very remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738; in 1738 there were three Basque ladies.
Grisóstomo's burial and Marcela's appearance and speech
14.1 Episode of Grisóstomo and Marcela, continuation14.3 Marcela’s appearance and speech14.4 Burial of Grisóstomo

During Grisóstomo's burial (center of the composition), Marcela appears on a crag; Ambrosio, Grisóstomo's friend, accuses her of causing his death.One diagonal (narration) joins these three main characters: from Marcela, through Ambrosio's face and arm, to Grisóstomo.This diagonal keeps in balanced with two verticals (a gravedigger on the left and don Quixote on the right).The scene is observed by Sancho Panza and several shepherds.Drawing and engraving are quite good.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote's night adventure with Maritornes

Don Quixote speaks to Maritornes as if she was a maiden and she flees away from him.On the left, the muleteer.This episode was first represented by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1675), but in a very different way.Savery was interested in the humorous fight between Sancho, Maritornes and the muleteer.Olfield and Vanderbank chose a funny moment not because of the action, but of the dialogue.Engraving and drawing are excellent.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.

From the whole episode, a comical/kind scene has been chosen to show the mutual care relation between don Quixote and Sancho.Don Quixote, after having fought with a flock of sheep, has been stoned by the shepherds; Sancho counts how many teeth remain in his mouth.Neither the previous fight nor the next scene (don Quixote and Sancho vomiting), both scenes of crude humour, were selected.In the background, the shepherds bringing the flock together.Drawing and engraving are very remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho Panza contemplates the barber basin (Mambrino's helmet)
21.3 Adventure of the helmet of Mambrino

In the foreground, Sancho contemplates the "conquered" Mambrino's helmet, a barber basin, and exclaims "Por Dios, que la bacía es buena, y que vale un real de á ocho como un maravedí" (21:2), while don Quixote asks him to hand the basin to him.In the background, the defeated barber running away.Well-detailed drawing and engraving for Don Quixote and Sancho's figures.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote asks the galley slaves about their crimes

Good example of the kind of scenes chosen by Oldfield and Vanderbank to be represented.Previously (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673), don Quixote had been represented fighting with the soldiers and stoned by the galley slaves; now, none of these scenes interest them.Don Quixote appears talking to the galley slaves (dialogue).Idealized image of the slaves, as "good savages".Excellent drawing and engraving (see gestures and hands: don Quixote, Sancho and slave on the left).
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after Baron's plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Dorotea is discovered by the priest, barber and Cardenio
28.1 Priest, barber and Cardenio encounter Dorotea

Dorotea, washing her feet in a stream, is discovered by the priest, the barber and Cardenio.This scene will be habitual in future editions.Dorotea could never be confused with a man (as it is said in Cervantes' text); she has been represented in woman clothes and showing her bosom.Bucolic setting.Drawing and engraving are very remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.

Vandervank has chosen as main character of this scene something almost anecdotal; next to don Quixote, who is attacking the wineskins, appears Dorotea, turning her head to avoid seeing don Quixote; "que vió quan corta y sutilmente estaba vestido, no quiso entrar á ver la batalla de su ayudador" (35:1).Dorotea´s figure (designed with an spiral movement) is excellently-drawn and engraved.In the background, Sancho, the innkeeper (both gesticulating), the priest and Cardenio.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote encounters some penitents with a sculpture of the Virgin Mary

From the whole episode, it has been chosen a non violent scene.Don Quixote orders the penitents to release the lady (a sculpture of the Virgin Mary) that they have taken prisoner.Sancho tries to stop him.The group of the penitents with the sculpture is not accurate to Spanish processions, but its composition has been resolved well.Drawing and engraving are very remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho talking with his wife, Teresa Panza, about his second sally
5.1 SP speaks with his wife Teresa

Interest in intimist and familiar scenes with dialogues.Teresa Panza answers to her husband, Sancho, about his second sally with don Quixote: "Advertid que Sanchico tiene ya quince años cabales, y es razón que vaya á la escuela [...]. Mirad, también, que Mari Sancha vuestra hija no se morirá si la casamos" (5:2).Well-detailed drawing and engraving; Sancho's figure is excellent.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sansón Carrasco proposes himself to be don Quixote's squire
7.2 Sansón Carrasco proposes DQ to be his squire

Sansón Carrasco proposes himself to be don Quixote's squire and don Quixote tells Sancho: "No te dije yo, Sancho, que no me habían de sobrar escuderos? (7:2), which causes Sancho's sadness.Sancho's sad face is remarkable; tender image.Notice how the dialogue has been developed through gestures and looks. Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced and turned format by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote helps Sancho to climb on a tree

From the whole episode, it has not been chosen don Quixote fighting or defeating the Knight of the Mirrors, but a previous and more tender scene. Don Quixote helps Sancho to climb on a tree because he is frightened of the big-nosed squire (Tomé Cecial disguised).On the left, the Knight of the Mirrors (Sansón Carrasco) and his squire.Drawing and engraving are quite good.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote relates his adventure into Montesinos' cave
23.1 DQ’s tale of his experience in the cave

Top: don Quixote tells Sancho and the bachelor's cousin what he has seen into Montesinos' cave (notice his hands).The bachelor's cousin listens to don Quixote attentively; Sancho with distrust (he knows the truth about Dulcinea's enchantment).Bottom: don Quixote's encounter with Montesinos and Durandarte (sketched as an imaginary or dreamt scene).Drawing, shading and engraving are quite remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.

Scene first represented by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657).Now, it has not been chosen the fight, but a previous and comical moment. Sancho's bray astonishes don Quixote and angers the members of the braying mayors squadron; "Uno de los que estaban junto a él, creyendo que hacía burla de ellos, alzó un varapalo" (27:2).Foreground figures' drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote and Sancho during the adventure of the enchanted boat

Don Quixote and Sancho, both in a boat, arrive dangerously to a mill wheel and the millers try to save them.Scene first represented in London: Hodgkin, 1687. Then, with a wide view; now, don Quixote and Sancho's expressions are more detailed (Sancho praying frightened; don Quixote threatening the millers that try to save them).Drawing and engraving are quite remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after Bosc's plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Pedro Recio does not allow Sancho to eat
47.1 SP not allowed to eat by Pedro Recio

In Barataria Island, Sancho is not allowed to eat by Pedro Recio, who orders the servants to take away the dishes.Since its representation by Coypel (Paris: Surugue, 1724), this scene is habitual in 18th century editions.Now, the composition is quite different; more austere setting (clothes, architectures...)and less artificial.On the right, Sancho, servants, the steward and the secretary.On the left, just Pedro Recio (framed by and arch).Drawing and engraving are excellent in Sancho's figure, but less remarkable in the others.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced and turned format by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
57.1 DQ leaves duke’s palace57.2 Altisidora’s false love for DQ

Don Quixote and Sancho are saying goodbye to the Duke and the Duchess when Altisidora appears to demand three night-coifs and a pair of garters.Wrongly-set scene.Vanderbank has represented the characters into a room, but Cervantes describes them at the palace courtyard.Figures of excellent drawing and engraving; Altisidora (of great beauty and carefully-done gesture) is specially remarkable.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.

In a galley, the General presents Ana Félix (in Moorish clothes and prepared to be hanged) to the Viceroy; behind them, don Quixote, Sancho Panza and Ricote as a pilgrim (Ana Félix's father) among several sailors.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but this illustration is not among the best ones of the set.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced and turned format by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote defeated by the Knight of the White Moon
64.1 DQ is defeated by the Knight of the White Moon (Sansón Carrasco)

In the foreground, don Quixote fallen on the ground and defeated by the Knight of the White Moon (Sansón Carrasco).In the background, Sancho Panza, Antonio Moreno, the Viceroy and others observe the scene.Set on Barcelona beach (galleys and walled port).Basic composition since Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657); now, more detailed and well-engraved.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced size by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote and Sancho abducted my armed men
68.2 DQ abducted and taken to the Dukes´ palace

Don Quixote and Sancho are abducted by several men armed with lances (Duke's servants); every time that don Quixote or Sancho try to speak, the men order them to keep quiet (see gestures).Composition divided in two groups: in the foreground, don Quixote and several men; in the background, Sancho and others.Drawing and engraving are quite remarkable; some figures have been resolved with skillful engraving; notice don Quixote's sad expression.
1 – Plate newly engraved in a reduced and turned format by Van der Gucht after his own plate with Vanderbank’s design first engraved for London: Tonson, 1738.
